{"title_page": "Buell F. Jones", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Buell F. Jones\n|image        = Buell F Jones, 11th Attorney General of South Dakota.jpg\n|order2        = 11th [[Attorney General of South Dakota]]\n|term_start2   = 1923\t\n|term_end2     = 1929\t\n|governor2     = [[William J. Bulow]]<br>[[Warren Green]]\n|predecessor2  = Byron S. Payne\n|successor2  =  Merrell Q. Sharpe\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1888|11|25}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1947|11|17|1892|11|25}}\n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = \n|profession  =Attorney\n| alma_mater  =[[University of South Dakota School of Law]]\n|religion    = \n}}\n\n'''Buell F. Jones''' (November 25, 1892 \u2013 November 17, 1947) was an American attorney and 11th [[Attorney General of South Dakota]] between 1923 and 1929. Born in [[Spain, South Dakota]], Buell graduated from the [[University of South Dakota School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1923 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he was elected in 1922 as Attorney General of South Dakota.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1923 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> He was re-elected in 1924,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1925 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> 1926,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1927 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> and 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1929 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Byron S. Payne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Attorney General of South Dakota]]}}|years=1923-1929}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Merrell Q. Sharpe]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current South Dakota statewide political officials |state=collapsed}}\n{{U.S. state attorneys general}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Buell}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of South Dakota School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Buell F. Jones\n|image        = Buell F Jones, 11th Attorney General of South Dakota.jpg\n|order2        = 11th [[Attorney General of South Dakota]]\n|term_start2   = 1923\t\n|term_end2     = 1929\t\n|governor2     = [[William J. Bulow]]<br>[[Warren Green]]\n|predecessor2  = Byron S. Payne\n|successor2  =  Merrell Q. Sharpe\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1888|11|25}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1947|11|17|1892|11|25}}\n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = \n|profession  =Attorney\n| alma_mater  =[[University of South Dakota School of Law]]\n|religion    = \n}}\n\n'''Buell F. Jones''' (November 25, 1892 \u2013 November 17, 1947) was an American attorney and 11th [[Attorney General of South Dakota]] between 1923 and 1929. Born in [[Spain, South Dakota]], Buell graduated from the [[University of South Dakota School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1923 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> A member of the [[Republican Party]], he was elected in 1922 as Attorney General of South Dakota.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1923 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> He was re-elected in 1924,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1925 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> 1926,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1927 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> and 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdsos.gov/general-information/blue-book-legislative-manual.aspx|title=Blue Book Legislative Manual, 1929 edition |publisher=sdsos.gov| accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Byron S. Payne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Attorney General of South Dakota]]}}|years=1923-1929}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Merrell Q. Sharpe]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current South Dakota statewide political officials |state=collapsed}}\n{{U.S. state attorneys general}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Buell}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:South Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of South Dakota School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Anas1712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Republican Party\u2192Republican Party (United States)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buell_F._Jones"}
{"title_page": "Bicyclomycin", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name               = (1S,6R)-6-Hydroxy-5-methylene-1-[(1'S,2'S)-1,2,3-trihydroxy-2-methylpropyl]-2-oxa-7,9-diazabicyclo[4.2.2]decane-8,10-dione\n| image                    = Bicyclomycin.svg\n| CAS_number               = 38129-37-2\n| CAS_supplemental         = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = J03U9E2P82\n| ATC_prefix               = None\n| ATC_suffix               = \n| DrugBank          = \n| ChemSpiderID      = 59222\n| smiles            = C[C@](CO)([C@@H]([C@@]12C(=O)N[C@@](C(=C)CCO1)(C(=O)N2)O)O)O\n| StdInChI          = 1S/C12H18N2O7/c1-6-3-4-21-12(7(16)10(2,19)5-15)9(18)13-11(6,20)8(17)14-12/h7,15-16,19-20H,1,3-5H2,2H3,(H,13,18)(H,14,17)/t7-,10-,11+,12-/m0/s1\n| StdInChIKey       = WOUDXEYYJPOSNE-VKZDFBPFSA-N\n| KEGG = C11259\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| ChEBI =  60584\n| PubChem = 65807\n| C=12 | H=18 | N=2 | O=7\n| molecular_weight         =  302.3 g/mol\n| bioavailability          = \n| protein_bound            = \n| metabolism               = \n| elimination_half-life    = \n| excretion                = \n| pregnancy_category       = \n| legal_status =\n| routes_of_administration = \n<!--Clinical data-->\n| pronounce = \n| tradename = bicozamycin\n}}\n\n'''Bicyclomycin''' ('''Bicozamycin''') is a broad spectrum antibiotic active against [[Gram-negative bacteria]] and the Gram-positive bacterium, ''Micrococcus luteus'' that was isolated<ref name=\"pmid4648311\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Miyoshi T, Miyairi N, Aoki H, Kohsaka M, Sakai HI, Imanaka H | title = Bicyclomycin, a new antibiotic | journal = The Journal of Antibiotics | volume = 25 | issue = 10 | pages = 569\u2013575 | date= 1972 | pmid = 4648311 | doi = 10.7164/antibiotics.25.569 | url =  }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid4648315\">{{cite journal |author1=Miyamura S |author2=Ogasawara N |author3=Otsuka H |author4=Niwayama S |author5=Tanaka H |author6=Take T |author7=Uchiyama T |author8=Ochiai H |author9=Abe K |author10=Koizumi K |author11=Asao K. Matsuki K |author12=Hoshino T | title = Antibiotic No. 5879, a new water-soluble antibiotic against gram-negative bacteria | journal = The Journal of Antibiotics | volume = 25 | issue = 10 | pages = 610\u2013612 | date= 1972 | pmid = 4648315 | doi = 10.7164/antibiotics.25.610 | url =  }}</ref> from ''Streptomyces sapporonesis'' and ''Streptomyces aizumenses'' in 1972.  It belongs to a class of naturally occurring [[2,5-Diketopiperazine|2,5-diketopiperazines]],<ref>{{Cite journal | title = 2,5-Diketopiperazines: Synthesis, Reactions, Medicinal Chemistry, and Bioactive Natural Products | author = Borthwick AD | journal = Chemical Reviews | year = 2012 | volume = 112 | issue = 7 | pages = 3641\u20133716 | doi = 10.1021/cr200398y | pmid = 22575049}}</ref> that are among the most numerous of all the naturally occurring peptide antibiotics.\nThis clinically useful antibiotic is rapidly absorbed in humans when given intramuscularly, has low toxicity and has been used to treat [[diarrhea]] in humans and bacterial diarrhea in calves and pigs.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kohn H, Widger W | title = The molecular basis for the mode of action of bicyclomycin | journal = Current Drug Targets. Infectious Disorders | volume = 5 | issue = 3 | pages = 273\u2013295 | date= September 2005 | pmid = 16181146 | doi = 10.2174/1568005054880136 | url =  }}</ref>\n\n==Mechanism of action==\nBicyclomycin is the only known selective inhibitor of Rho, a [[RecA]]-type [[ATPase]], which is a transcription [[termination factor]] in ''[[Escherichia coli]]''.  X-ray crystallographic images of the bicyclomycin-rho complex have been used to define the rho antibiotic-binding site and understand the molecular basis for its mode of action.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\" />\n\n==Physical properties==\nBicyclomycin is a crystalline, colorless, water-soluble, and weakly basic substance (mp 187-189 <sup>o</sup>C) that is soluble in methanol, and sparingly in ethanol, is practically insoluble in most organic solvents, and is unstable in alkaline solution.<ref name=\"ChemRev\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Williams RM, Durham CA | title = Bicyclomycin: Synthetic, mechanistic, and biological studies | journal = Chemical Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 3 | pages = 511\u2013540 | date= May 1988 | doi = 10.1021/cr00085a004 | url =  }}</ref>\n\n==Structure\u2013activity relationships and Antibiotic potency==\n\n[[File:Pharmacophore of Bicyclomycin.svg|left|thumb|300px|The (1''S'', 6''R'', 1\u2019''S'', 2\u2019''S'')-stereochemistry and pharmacophore (in orange and black) required for good activity]]\n\nIn an attempt to increase the potency and its antimicrobial spectrum, a series of synthetic and semisynthetic derivatives were investigated.\n[[Structure\u2013activity relationship]] (SAR) studies have shown that the C(1) triol and the [4.2.2]-bicyclic ring were essential for bicyclomycin-rho inhibitory activity whereas the C(5)\u2212C(5a) exomethylene moiety was not.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\" />  Further SAR studies<ref name=\"pmid15725032\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Brogan AP, Widger WR, Bensadek D, Riba-Garcia I, Gaskell SJ, Kohn H | title = Development of a technique to determine bicyclomycin-rho binding and stoichiometry by isothermal titration calorimetry and mass spectrometry | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | volume = 127 | issue = 8 | pages = 2741\u20132751 | date= March 2005 | pmid = 15725032 | doi = 10.1021/ja046441q | url =  }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid16185879\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Park BS, Widger W, Kohn H | title = Fluorine-substituted dihydrobicyclomycins: Synthesis and biochemical and biological properties | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 14 | issue = 1 | pages = 41\u201361 | date= January 2006 | pmid = 16185879 | doi =10.1016/j.bmc.2005.07.075 | url =  }}</ref> showed that 5a-substituted derivatives can be prepared that were an order of magnitude more efficient than bicyclomycin in the inhibition of rho.\nBicyclomycin is considered a weak antibiotic<ref name=\"ChemRev\" /> and when used alone, bicyclomycin failed to rapidly kill growing cultures of Escherichia coli; however, the additional presence of [[bacteriostatic]] concentrations of inhibitors of gene expression such as [[tetracycline]], [[chloramphenicol]] or [[rifampicin]] led to rapid killing.<ref name=\"pmid 25085655\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Malik M, Li L, Zhao X, Kerns RJ, Berger JM, Drlica K | title = Lethal synergy involving bicyclomycin: an approach for reviving old antibiotics | journal = Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy | volume = 69 | issue = 12 | pages = 3227\u20133235 | date= July 2014 | pmid = 25085655 | doi = 10.1093/jac/dku285 | pmc=4228776}}</ref>  This lethal synergy has been considered as one way to address the growing problem of [[antimicrobial resistance]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Synthesis==\nBicyclomycin, initially produced on large scale from the fermentation harvest of an improved strain of ''S. sapporonensis'',<ref name=\"ChemRev\" /> has also been synthesised; many derivatives have also been prepared.<ref name=\"ChemRev\" />  Most of the synthetic approaches to bicyclomycin have started with a preformed 2,5-diketopiperazine.<ref name=\"ChemRev\" />\n[[File:Synthesis of Bicyclomycin.svg|center|600px|Synthetic route to Bicyclomycin]]\nWilliams synthesis<ref name=\"SynBicyclo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Williams RM, Armstrong RW, Dung JS | title = Stereocontrolled total synthesis of (.+-.)-and (+)-bicyclomycin | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | volume = 107 | issue = 11 | pages = 3253\u2013326 | date= May 1985 | doi = 10.1021/ja00297a035 | url =  }}</ref> starts from the ''para''-methoxybenzyl protected 2,5-diketopiperazine '''1''', ''bis'' bromination to give the 3,6-dibromide followed by thiolate displacements with sodio-2-thiopyridine gave the ''syn'' di(thiopyridine) derivative which was condensed with the silyl ketene acetal of y-butyrolactone in presence of [[silver triflate]] (AgOTf) to give the mono lactone which upon reduction with LiAlH<sub>4</sub> afforded the diol '''2'''.  Cyclization of '''2''' in the presence of silver triflate gave the bicyclo-[4.2.2] alcohol '''3'''.  Dehydration to the key olefin proceeded in good overall yield followed by bridgehead carbanion oxidation with molecular oxygen gave the single hydroxylation product '''4'''. Formation of the dianion of '''4''' followed by [[aldol reaction]] with acetal aldehyde '''5''' gave the aldol product with the desired relative configuration.  Protection of the C-1'-hydroxyl as the corresponding trifluoroacetate followed by cleavage of the acetonide and p-methoxybenzyl groups with [[ceric ammonium nitrate]] followed by [[methanolysis]] on silica gel gave racemic bicyclomycin '''6'''.  Use of the optically active aldehyde analogue of '''5''' allowed preparation of optically active '''6'''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n<!-- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. -->\n\n[[Category:Diketopiperazines]]\n[[Category:Antibiotics]]\n[[Category:Bicyclic compounds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name               = (1S,6R)-6-Hydroxy-5-methylene-1-[(1'S,2'S)-1,2,3-trihydroxy-2-methylpropyl]-2-oxa-7,9-diazabicyclo[4.2.2]decane-8,10-dione\n| image                    = Bicyclomycin.svg\n| CAS_number               = 38129-37-2\n| CAS_supplemental         = \n| ATC_prefix               = None\n| ATC_suffix               = \n| DrugBank          = \n| ChemSpiderID      = 59222\n| smiles            = C[C@](CO)([C@@H]([C@@]12C(=O)N[C@@](C(=C)CCO1)(C(=O)N2)O)O)O\n| StdInChI          = 1S/C12H18N2O7/c1-6-3-4-21-12(7(16)10(2,19)5-15)9(18)13-11(6,20)8(17)14-12/h7,15-16,19-20H,1,3-5H2,2H3,(H,13,18)(H,14,17)/t7-,10-,11+,12-/m0/s1\n| StdInChIKey       = WOUDXEYYJPOSNE-VKZDFBPFSA-N\n| KEGG = C11259\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| ChEBI =  60584\n| PubChem = 65807\n| C=12 | H=18 | N=2 | O=7\n| molecular_weight         =  302.3 g/mol\n| bioavailability          = \n| protein_bound            = \n| metabolism               = \n| elimination_half-life    = \n| excretion                = \n| pregnancy_category       = \n| legal_status =\n| routes_of_administration = \n<!--Clinical data-->\n| pronounce = \n| tradename = bicozamycin\n}}\n\n'''Bicyclomycin''' ('''Bicozamycin''') is a broad spectrum antibiotic active against [[Gram-negative bacteria]] and the Gram-positive bacterium, ''Micrococcus luteus'' that was isolated<ref name=\"pmid4648311\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Miyoshi T, Miyairi N, Aoki H, Kohsaka M, Sakai HI, Imanaka H | title = Bicyclomycin, a new antibiotic | journal = The Journal of Antibiotics | volume = 25 | issue = 10 | pages = 569\u2013575 | date= 1972 | pmid = 4648311 | doi = 10.7164/antibiotics.25.569 | url =  }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid4648315\">{{cite journal |author1=Miyamura S |author2=Ogasawara N |author3=Otsuka H |author4=Niwayama S |author5=Tanaka H |author6=Take T |author7=Uchiyama T |author8=Ochiai H |author9=Abe K |author10=Koizumi K |author11=Asao K. Matsuki K |author12=Hoshino T | title = Antibiotic No. 5879, a new water-soluble antibiotic against gram-negative bacteria | journal = The Journal of Antibiotics | volume = 25 | issue = 10 | pages = 610\u2013612 | date= 1972 | pmid = 4648315 | doi = 10.7164/antibiotics.25.610 | url =  }}</ref> from ''Streptomyces sapporonesis'' and ''Streptomyces aizumenses'' in 1972.  It belongs to a class of naturally occurring [[2,5-Diketopiperazine|2,5-diketopiperazines]],<ref>{{Cite journal | title = 2,5-Diketopiperazines: Synthesis, Reactions, Medicinal Chemistry, and Bioactive Natural Products | author = Borthwick AD | journal = Chemical Reviews | year = 2012 | volume = 112 | issue = 7 | pages = 3641\u20133716 | doi = 10.1021/cr200398y | pmid = 22575049}}</ref> that are among the most numerous of all the naturally occurring peptide antibiotics.\nThis clinically useful antibiotic is rapidly absorbed in humans when given intramuscularly, has low toxicity and has been used to treat [[diarrhea]] in humans and bacterial diarrhea in calves and pigs.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kohn H, Widger W | title = The molecular basis for the mode of action of bicyclomycin | journal = Current Drug Targets. Infectious Disorders | volume = 5 | issue = 3 | pages = 273\u2013295 | date= September 2005 | pmid = 16181146 | doi = 10.2174/1568005054880136 | url =  }}</ref>\n\n==Mechanism of action==\nBicyclomycin is the only known selective inhibitor of Rho, a [[RecA]]-type [[ATPase]], which is a transcription [[termination factor]] in ''[[Escherichia coli]]''.  X-ray crystallographic images of the bicyclomycin-rho complex have been used to define the rho antibiotic-binding site and understand the molecular basis for its mode of action.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\" />\n\n==Physical properties==\nBicyclomycin is a crystalline, colorless, water-soluble, and weakly basic substance (mp 187-189 <sup>o</sup>C) that is soluble in methanol, and sparingly in ethanol, is practically insoluble in most organic solvents, and is unstable in alkaline solution.<ref name=\"ChemRev\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Williams RM, Durham CA | title = Bicyclomycin: Synthetic, mechanistic, and biological studies | journal = Chemical Reviews | volume = 88 | issue = 3 | pages = 511\u2013540 | date= May 1988 | doi = 10.1021/cr00085a004 | url =  }}</ref>\n\n==Structure\u2013activity relationships and Antibiotic potency==\n\n[[File:Pharmacophore of Bicyclomycin.svg|left|thumb|300px|The (1''S'', 6''R'', 1\u2019''S'', 2\u2019''S'')-stereochemistry and pharmacophore (in orange and black) required for good activity]]\n\nIn an attempt to increase the potency and its antimicrobial spectrum, a series of synthetic and semisynthetic derivatives were investigated.\n[[Structure\u2013activity relationship]] (SAR) studies have shown that the C(1) triol and the [4.2.2]-bicyclic ring were essential for bicyclomycin-rho inhibitory activity whereas the C(5)\u2212C(5a) exomethylene moiety was not.<ref name=\"pmid16181146\" />  Further SAR studies<ref name=\"pmid15725032\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Brogan AP, Widger WR, Bensadek D, Riba-Garcia I, Gaskell SJ, Kohn H | title = Development of a technique to determine bicyclomycin-rho binding and stoichiometry by isothermal titration calorimetry and mass spectrometry | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | volume = 127 | issue = 8 | pages = 2741\u20132751 | date= March 2005 | pmid = 15725032 | doi = 10.1021/ja046441q | url =  }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid16185879\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Park BS, Widger W, Kohn H | title = Fluorine-substituted dihydrobicyclomycins: Synthesis and biochemical and biological properties | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 14 | issue = 1 | pages = 41\u201361 | date= January 2006 | pmid = 16185879 | doi =10.1016/j.bmc.2005.07.075 | url =  }}</ref> showed that 5a-substituted derivatives can be prepared that were an order of magnitude more efficient than bicyclomycin in the inhibition of rho.\nBicyclomycin is considered a weak antibiotic<ref name=\"ChemRev\" /> and when used alone, bicyclomycin failed to rapidly kill growing cultures of Escherichia coli; however, the additional presence of [[bacteriostatic]] concentrations of inhibitors of gene expression such as [[tetracycline]], [[chloramphenicol]] or [[rifampicin]] led to rapid killing.<ref name=\"pmid 25085655\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Malik M, Li L, Zhao X, Kerns RJ, Berger JM, Drlica K | title = Lethal synergy involving bicyclomycin: an approach for reviving old antibiotics | journal = Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy | volume = 69 | issue = 12 | pages = 3227\u20133235 | date= July 2014 | pmid = 25085655 | doi = 10.1093/jac/dku285 | pmc=4228776}}</ref>  This lethal synergy has been considered as one way to address the growing problem of [[antimicrobial resistance]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Synthesis==\nBicyclomycin, initially produced on large scale from the fermentation harvest of an improved strain of ''S. sapporonensis'',<ref name=\"ChemRev\" /> has also been synthesised; many derivatives have also been prepared.<ref name=\"ChemRev\" />  Most of the synthetic approaches to bicyclomycin have started with a preformed 2,5-diketopiperazine.<ref name=\"ChemRev\" />\n[[File:Synthesis of Bicyclomycin.svg|center|600px|Synthetic route to Bicyclomycin]]\nWilliams synthesis<ref name=\"SynBicyclo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Williams RM, Armstrong RW, Dung JS | title = Stereocontrolled total synthesis of (.+-.)-and (+)-bicyclomycin | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | volume = 107 | issue = 11 | pages = 3253\u2013326 | date= May 1985 | doi = 10.1021/ja00297a035 | url =  }}</ref> starts from the ''para''-methoxybenzyl protected 2,5-diketopiperazine '''1''', ''bis'' bromination to give the 3,6-dibromide followed by thiolate displacements with sodio-2-thiopyridine gave the ''syn'' di(thiopyridine) derivative which was condensed with the silyl ketene acetal of y-butyrolactone in presence of [[silver triflate]] (AgOTf) to give the mono lactone which upon reduction with LiAlH<sub>4</sub> afforded the diol '''2'''.  Cyclization of '''2''' in the presence of silver triflate gave the bicyclo-[4.2.2] alcohol '''3'''.  Dehydration to the key olefin proceeded in good overall yield followed by bridgehead carbanion oxidation with molecular oxygen gave the single hydroxylation product '''4'''. Formation of the dianion of '''4''' followed by [[aldol reaction]] with acetal aldehyde '''5''' gave the aldol product with the desired relative configuration.  Protection of the C-1'-hydroxyl as the corresponding trifluoroacetate followed by cleavage of the acetonide and p-methoxybenzyl groups with [[ceric ammonium nitrate]] followed by [[methanolysis]] on silica gel gave racemic bicyclomycin '''6'''.  Use of the optically active aldehyde analogue of '''5''' allowed preparation of optically active '''6'''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n<!-- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. -->\n\n[[Category:Diketopiperazines]]\n[[Category:Antibiotics]]\n[[Category:Bicyclic compounds]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicyclomycin"}
{"title_page": "Estrellados", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Estrellados\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        =\n| director       = Salvador de Alberich<br>[[Edward Sedgwick]]\n| producer       = [[Buster Keaton]]\n| screenplay     = Salvador de Alberich<br>[[Paul Dickey]]<br>[[Richard Schayer]]\n| starring       = Buster Keaton<br>[[Raquel Torres]]<br>[[Don Alvarado]]<br>Mar\u00eda Calvo<br>Juan de Homs<br>[[Carlos Villar\u00edas]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Leonard Smith (cinematographer)|Leonard Smith]]\n| editing        = George Boemler \n| studio         = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| distributor    = Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer\n| released       = {{Film date|1930|7|7}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Estrellados''''' is a 1930 American [[Pre-Code Hollywood|pre-Code]] [[comedy film]] directed by Salvador de Alberich and [[Edward Sedgwick]], and written by Salvador de Alberich, [[Paul Dickey]] and [[Richard Schayer]]. The film stars [[Buster Keaton]], [[Raquel Torres]], [[Don Alvarado]], Mar\u00eda Calvo, Juan de Homs and [[Carlos Villar\u00edas]]. \n\nThe film was released on July 7, 1930, by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]. The film serves as the Spanish-language version of ''[[Free and Easy (1930 film)|Free and Easy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/414478/Estrellados/|title=Estrellados (1930) - Overview - TCM.com|work=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=775|title=Estrellados|publisher=AFI|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{no plot|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Buster Keaton]] as Canuto Cuadratin\n*[[Raquel Torres]] as Elvira Rosas\n*[[Don Alvarado]] as Larry Mitchell\n*Mar\u00eda Calvo as La Mam\u00e0 Rosas\n*Juan de Homs as Director\n*[[Carlos Villar\u00edas]] as Jack Collier\n*[[Lionel Barrymore]] as Himself \n*[[William Haines]] as Himself \n*[[John Miljan]] as Himself \n*[[Gwen Lee]] as Herself \n*[[Cecil B. DeMille]] as Himself \n*[[Fred Niblo]] as Himself\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0216742|Estrellados}}\n\n{{Edward Sedgwick}}\n\n[[Category:1930 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:1930s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Sedgwick]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:1930s multilingual films]]\n\n{{1930s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Estrellados\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        =\n| director       = Salvador de Alberich<br>[[Edward Sedgwick]]\n| producer       = [[Buster Keaton]]\n| screenplay     = Salvador de Alberich<br>[[Paul Dickey]]<br>[[Richard Schayer]]\n| starring       = Buster Keaton<br>[[Raquel Torres]]<br>[[Don Alvarado]]<br>Mar\u00eda Calvo<br>Juan de Homs<br>[[Carlos Villar\u00edas]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Leonard Smith (cinematographer)|Leonard Smith]]\n| editing        = George Boemler \n| studio         = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| distributor    = Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer\n| released       = {{Film date|1930|7|7}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Estrellados''''' is a 1930 American [[Pre-Code Hollywood|pre-Code]] [[comedy film]] directed by Salvador de Alberich and [[Edward Sedgwick]], and written by Salvador de Alberich, [[Paul Dickey]] and [[Richard Schayer]]. The film stars [[Buster Keaton]], [[Raquel Torres]], [[Don Alvarado]], Mar\u00eda Calvo, Juan de Homs and [[Carlos Villar\u00edas]]. \n\nThe film was released on July 7, 1930, by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]. The film serves as the Spanish language version of ''[[Free and Easy (1930 film)|Free and Easy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/414478/Estrellados/|title=Estrellados (1930) - Overview - TCM.com|work=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=775|title=Estrellados|publisher=AFI|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{no plot|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Buster Keaton]] as Canuto Cuadratin\n*[[Raquel Torres]] as Elvira Rosas\n*[[Don Alvarado]] as Larry Mitchell\n*Mar\u00eda Calvo as La Mam\u00e0 Rosas\n*Juan de Homs as Director\n*[[Carlos Villar\u00edas]] as Jack Collier\n*[[Lionel Barrymore]] as Himself \n*[[William Haines]] as Himself \n*[[John Miljan]] as Himself \n*[[Gwen Lee]] as Herself \n*[[Cecil B. DeMille]] as Himself \n*[[Fred Niblo]] as Himself\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0216742|Estrellados}}\n\n{{Edward Sedgwick}}\n\n[[Category:1930 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:1930s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Sedgwick]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:1930s multilingual films]]\n\n{{1930s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: Spanish language \u2192 Spanish-language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estrellados"}
{"title_page": "Siliguri", "text_new": "{{short description|City in West Bengal, India}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Siliguri\n| other_name                      =\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolitan City]] / [[Urban Agglomeration]]\n| image_skyline                   = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a = Siliguri view.jpg\n| photo2a = Siliguri view 19.jpg\n| photo2b = Siliguri view 20.jpg\n| photo3a = Siliguri view 16.jpg\n| photo4a = Siliguri view 5.jpg\n| photo4b = Siliguri view 11.jpg\n | size = 250\n | spacing = 1\n | border = 0\n | color = White\n| position = centre\n| foot_montage = TOP TO BOTTOM : <br/>Old view of Siliguri , ISKCON temple(left) , Heritage Toy Train at Siliguri Junction(right) , Ewam India Monastery , Lions clock tower(left) , Science centre Siliguri(right).}}\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in West Bengal##Location in India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|26.71|N|88.43|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{IND}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_type3               = No. of [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|Wards]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Darjeeling district|Darjeeling (62%)]], [[Jalpaiguri district|Jalpaiguri (38%)]]\n| subdivision_name3               = 47<ref>{{