oenkaschool.in/|title=G.D. Goenka Public School, Siliguri - Home - No1 residential School|website=Gdgoenkaschool.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*IICE Educational Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iice.online/|title=IICE Academy Siliguri Admission in NIOS Board for Drop Out Student|website=Iice.online|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Jermel's Academy (CBSE)\n*Lincolns High School (ICSE)\n*Margaret (S.N.) English High School\n*Modi Public School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mpssiliguri.com/|title=Modi Public School, Siliguri|website=Mpssiliguri.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Narayana School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.narayanaschools.in/siliguri/|title=Siliguri - Narayana Schools|website=Marayanaschools.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*New St. John's School & High School (WBBSE & WBBHSE) (Co-Ed)\n*Nirmala Convent School (ICSE)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nirmalaconventschoolsiliguri.com/|title=Home - Nirmala Convent School|website=Nirmalaconventschoolsiliguri.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*North Point Residential School, CBSE\n*Royal Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royalacademysiliguri.com/|title=Royal Academy|website=Royalacademysiliguri.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Sacred Heart High school (ICSE)\n*Shri Krishna Pranami Vidya Niketan (CBSE)\n*Shri Ram Centennial School<<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.srcs.edu.in/|title=Shri Ram Centennial School, Siliguri|website=Srcs.edu.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*St. Joseph School, Bhaktinagar<ref>{{cite web |title=Home {{!}} ST. JOSEPH SCHOOL |url=https://www.sjsnjp.org/ |website=ST. JOSEPH SCHOOL, B |accessdate=25 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*St. Joseph's High School (ICSE)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjhsm.in/|title=St Joseph's High School, Matigara - Home|website=Sjhsm.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*St. Michael's School (ICSE)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smsslg.com/|title=Home|website=Smsslg.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*St. Xavier's School (ICSE)\n\n;Hindi Medium Schools\n*Bharati Hindi Vidyalaya\n*Dr. Rajendra Prasad Girl's High School\n*Hindi Balika Vidyapith<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hbvidyapith.in/|title=H B Vidyapith, CBSE School, Siliguri|website=Hbvidyapith.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Siliguri Hindi High School\n\n;Nepali Medium Schools\n*Dr. I.B. Thapa Nepali Vidyalaya\n*Ravi Ratna Dhungana School\n\n; Muslim Schools\n*Shamsia High Madrasah (Co-ed)\n\n;Army Schools\n*Army Public School (Bengdubi & Khaprail)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsbengdubi.org/|title=Army Public School, Bengdubi|website=Apsbengdubi.org|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Army Public School, Sukna<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apssukna.com/|title=Army Public School, Sukna|website=Apssukna.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*BSF Senior Secoundry School Kadamtala<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bsfschoolkadamtala.org/|title=BSF SENIOR SECONDARY RESIDENTIAL SCHOOL, Kadamtala, Darjeeling :: Welcome|website=Bsfschoolkadamtala.org|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Kendriya Vidyalayas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kvsevokeroad.in/|title=Kendriya Vidyalaya, Sevoke Road :: Home Page|website=Kvsevokeroad.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Railway Schools\n*Bani Mandir Railway H.S. School (Co-ed)\n*New Jalpaiguri Railway Colony H.S. (Co-ed)\n*Railway Girls High School\n\n==Media==\n\n; Newspaper :English newspapers including [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.telegraphindia.com/north%20bangal/2019-06-06/72/Page-1.html|title=The Telegraph Siliguri edition epaper|website=epaper.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Times of India]] , [[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.thestatesman.com/t/9248|title=The Statesman Siliguri edition|website=www.uttarbangasambad.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> The Economic Time, [[The Asian Age]] are widely circulated throughout the city. Several Bengali newspaper including [[Uttarbanga Sambad]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uttarbangasambad.in/|title=Uttarbanga Sambad Siliguri edition|website=www.uttarbangasambad.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Anandabazar Patrika]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.anandabazar.com/topic/siliguri|title=Anandabazar Patrika Siliguri edition|website=www.anandabazar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Bartaman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bartamanpatrika.com/contact.php?cID=39|title=Bartaman Patrika Siliguri edition|website=www.bartamanpatrika.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Uttarer Saradin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highmediaindia.com/Media/contact_us.html|title=Uttarer Saradin-High Media Infotainment India Ltd.|website=www.highmediaindia.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Aajkaal]], Pratidin, [[Ganashakti]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangla.ganashakti.co.in/#page1|title=Ganashakti patrika Siliguri edition|website=bangla.ganashakti.co.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> are available. Leading Hindi daily [[Prabhat Khabar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.prabhatkhabar.com/t/6235/Siliguri-City/?s=si|title=Prabhat Khabar Siliguri edition|website=epaper.prabhatkhabar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prabhatkhabar.com/news/west-bengal/siliguri/|title=Prabhat Khabar newspaper-Siliguri news|website=epaper.prabhatkhabar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> and Janpath Samachar<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janpathsamachar.com/epaper.php?pageid=page1&date=070619|title=Janpath Samachar Siliguri edition epaper|website=www.janpathsamachar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> are also published from Siliguri. 'Himalaya Darpan' is a notable Nepali language newspaper which is circulated in Siliguri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaperhimalayadarpan.com/|title=Himalaya Darpan-news portal|website=www.epaperhimalayadarpan.com|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> An online based news portal, Siliguri Times<ref>{{cite web|url=https://siliguritimes.com/category/news/siliguri/amp/|title=SiliguriTimes-news portal|website=www.siliguritimes.com|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> is there for providing live updates regarding Siliguri and adjacent areas.\n\n;Radio : [[All India Radio]] Siliguri was commissioned in 1963 as an additional station of [[All India Radio|AIR Kolkata]].<ref name=\"AIR Siliguri-history\">{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=AIR Siliguri-history|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> It has two groups of transmitter i.e. high power BEL HMB 140 (AM) -2 [2\u00d7100 kW] and medium range GCEL 136 (FM) - 2 [2\u00d75 kW] for broadcasting programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/technical.html|title=AIR Siliguri-technical information|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> 'Prantik' was the first program broadcast from here in 1969.<ref name=\"AIR Siliguri-history\"/> In the course of time many notable individuals like [[Hemanta Mukhopadhyay]], [[Ustad Rashid Khan]], [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhas Mukhopadhyay]], [[Shashi Kapoor]], [[Manabendra Mukhopadhyay]], [[Madhuri Chattopadhyay]], Priya Ranjan Dasmunshi etc. visited [[All India Radio|AIR]] Siliguri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=Notable individuals visited AIR Siliguri|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Popular programs executing from here are Pratyusha, Yuva Anusthan, Grame Ganje, Mahila Majlis, Mananiyeshu, Sishumahal\u00a0and\u00a0Arogya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=Programs list of AIR Siliguri|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Two radio channels are operated from [[All India Radio|AIR]] Siliguri through which programs are broadcasting daily :\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| No.\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Name<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airsiliguri.in/station-profile.html|title=AIR Siliguri- broadcasting channels|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Frequency<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airsiliguri.in/station-profile.html|title=AIR Siliguri- frequency details|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Language\n|-\n|01|| Primary Channel (PC) || PC: 421.9\u00a0Metres 711&nbsp;kHz (Medium wave) || Bengali\n|-\n|02|| Vividh\u00a0Bharati\u00a0Service (VBS) || VBS: 101.4&nbsp;MHz (High wave) || Bengali/Hindi\n|}\n\n:In addition to [[All India Radio]], Siliguri has several private FM radio channels :\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:95%; width:30%;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| No.\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Name<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiawaves.net/india/west-bengal-radio.htm#siliguri-radio|title=Siliguri FM channels names|website=www.asiawaves.net|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radio-asia.org/fm/fm.php?itu=India&region=WB|title=FM stations in West Bengal|website=www.radio-asia.org|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Frequency<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiawaves.net/india/west-bengal-radio.htm#siliguri-radio|title=Siliguri FM channels frequency|website=www.asiawaves.net|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Language\n|-\n|01|| Nine FM || 91.9 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|02|| Radio High<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiohigh927fm.com/|title=Radio High 92.7 FM channel Siliguri|website=www.radiohigh927fm.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> || 92.7 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|03|| [[Red FM 93.5|Red FM]] || 93.5 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|04|| Radio Misty || 94.3 FM || Bengali \n|-\n|05|| Radio Mirchi || 98.3 FM || Bengali\n|-\n|06|| Air Rainbow<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlineradiofm.in/west-bengal/kurseong/fm-rainbow|title=Air rainbow Kurseong-Siliguri FM channel names|website=www.onlineradiofm.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> || 102.3 FM || Hindi/English\n|}\n\n;Television : Siliguri receives almost all television channels those are received by rest of the country. Apart from the national terrestrial network [[DD Bangla|Doordarshan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddbangla.gov.in/|title=DD Bangla-State owned channel|website=www.ddbangla.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://doordarshan.gov.in/|title=Doordarshan national|website=www.doordarshan.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> cable TV serves most of the houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://main.trai.gov.in/siliguri-internet-cable-tv-private-limited|title=Siliguri Internet & Cable TV Private Limited |website=main.trai.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccom.in/|title=CCN Siliguri cable network|website=www.cccom.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Siliguri also receives some Nepali<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abntv.in/|title=ABN TV Nepali TV channel|website=www.abntv.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> and Bangladeshi channels too. Siliguri has three local channels: CCN,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccom.in/|title=CCN Siliguri|website=www.cccom.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Amar Cable and HTV. There is a TV tower in Kurseong,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://doordarshan.gov.in/west-bengal-1|title=Doordarshan west Bengal stations|website=www.doordarshan.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> about 25&nbsp;km from Siliguri.\n\n==Sports facilities==\nSiliguri hosts numerous sporting events and matches to influence and build up young athletes from the city.  Some of the important sports enthusiast local clubs in Siliguri organise several cricket, football, volleyball, swimming competition, TT matches etc.  S.A.I or [[Sports Authority of India]] in Kanchenjunga Stadium conducts football and athletics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkfile/File1374.pdf|title=Sports Authority of India-Siliguri|website=www.sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> With the provision for an international outdoor and indoor stadium, Siliguri has enough opportunities to host national level matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/siliguri-prepares-for-big-battle/cid/1324566|title=Third I-League matches in Kanchanjunga stadium|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> This has also led to Siliguri being a prominent city to produce national champions like Mantu Ghosh, the Gold Medalist winner in the bi-annual South Asian Games (SAF) for table tennis, [[Ankita Das]],<ref name=\"champs\"/> [[Nandita Saha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/team/6241|title=Table Tennis Team-Women Melbourne 2006|publisher=thecgf.com|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> and [[Soumyajit Ghosh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120513/spectrum/main6.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref> another internationally acclaimed table tennis player and [[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian international [[cricket]]er who plays [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for [[India national cricket team|Indian national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;keeper=1;orderby=player;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;team=6;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|title=Wriddhiman Saha stats|website=espncricinfo|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> Siliguri has done a tremendous job for Indian table tennis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/siliguri-hailed-as-bhiwani-of-indian-tt-after-twin-oly-berth_741306.html|title=Siliguri hailed as Bhiwani of Indian TT|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=22 April 2012}}</ref> Also there is '''Bikash Ghosh Memorial Swimming Pool''' beside Kanchanjunga stadium in city which conducts swimming competitions there. White water rafting also done nearby the city in [[Teesta river]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.darjeeling-tourism.com/darj_0000f1.htm|title=white water rafting in Teesta river|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=400|caption_align=center\n| image1 = Sports 6.jpg|caption1=U-19 football tournament at [[Kanchenjunga Stadium]], Siliguri.\n| image2 = Sports 2.jpg|caption2=Municipal corporation indoor stadium.}}\n\n===Kanchenjunga stadium===\nThis is the main stadium in Siliguri,<ref>{{cite web | title =  Kanchenjunga Stadium in Siliguri |publisher=World Stadiums| url = http://www.worldstadiums.com/stadium_pictures/asia/india/siliguri_kanchenjunga.shtml | accessdate = 1 May 2019 }}</ref> a multipurpose stadium, mainly used for football matches although it hosted several cricket matches till date. It has a capacity of 30,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.millenniumpost.in/kolkata/kanchenjunga-stadium-set-to-get-a-facelift-342689|title=Kunchenjunga stadium-about|website=www.mellenniumpost.in|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=27 February 2019}}</ref> people at a time. Recently this stadium is all set to get a facelift.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kolkata24x7.com/kanchenjunga-stadium-set-to-get-major-makeover.html/|title=Kunchenjunga stadium all set to get facelift|website=www.kolkata24\u00d77.com|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Football:''' \n*This stadium hosted [[Federation Cup (India)|Federation Cup 2012]] matches of India . The first ever [[Federation Cup (India)|Federation Cup]] played on this ground was between [[Mohun Bagan AC]] and [[Churchill Brothers S.C.]] in 2012.\n*Final match of the [[2013\u201314 Santosh Trophy]] was played at the stadium in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | title = Clinical Mizoram clinch 68th Santosh Trophy in style | url = http://www.saharasamay.com/sports-news/676549354/clinical-mizoram-clinch-68th-santosh-trophy-in-style.html|publisher=Samay Live |date=10 March 2014| accessdate = 1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*Seven rounds of [[2015 I-League 2nd Division]] match was played on this ground.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second division league venues finalized|url=https://www.the-aiff.com/news-center-details.htm?id=6248|website=The All India Football Federation|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*It also hosted two [[Kolkata Derby|kolkata derby]] matches in [[2015\u201316 I-League 2nd Division|2016 I-league]].\n*All the matches of [[2016 SAFF Women's Championship]] were played in the Kanchenjunga Stadium in Siliguri, [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SAFF Women\u00b4s Championship To Be Held in Siliguri|url=http://goalie365.com/show_details.php?article_id=774|website= goalie365.com | date=11 November 2016 | accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Kolkata Derby|Third I-League derby]] matches was held in this stadium ground in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/siliguri-prepares-for-big-battle/cid/1324566|title=Third I-League matches supposed to held in Siliguri|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Cricket:'''\n*This stadium has hosted 11 [[Ranji Trophy]] matches.The first ever [[Ranji Trophy]] played on this ground was between [[Bengal cricket team|Bengal]] and [[Punjab cricket team (India)|Punjab]] in 2010.\n*Two [[Celebrity Cricket League]] matches were played here. The first ever [[Celebrity Cricket League]] played on this ground was between [[Veer Marathi]] vs [[Karnataka Bulldozers]] and [[Telugu Warriors]] vs [[Bengal Tigers (Celebrity Cricket League)|Bengal Tigers]] in 2013.\n\n===Municipal corporation indoor stadium===\nIndoor sports including [[Table tennis]], [[Badminton]], [[Taekwon-do]], [[Lawn tennis]] and [[Chess]] are being played here.In fact Siliguri is renowned for being the training grounds of table tennis players.This stadium can hold 5000 people at a time. Senior National Table Tennis Championship<ref>{{cite web|title =National table tennis championships 2017 results|url=http://ttfi.org/cmspages/results/Result%20-%202017|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> was recently organised here.<ref>{{cite web|title =National table tennis championships|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/tournament-in-paddlers-hub-siliguri/cid/1524036|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> Sports festival, 2017 also held in this indoor stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://siliguritimes.com/sports-festival-begins-indoor-stadium-siliguri/|title=Sports festival, Siliguri|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Visitors Attractions==\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=400|caption_align=center\n| image1 = Tourism 3.jpg|caption1=The [[Coronation Bridge]].\n| image2 = Tourism 2.jpg|caption2=Heritage [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|Toy Train]] at [[New Jalpaiguri Junction railway station|NJP]].\n| image3 = Tourism 5.jpg|caption3=Bengal safari park.\n| image4 = Tourism 8.jpg|caption4=Gajoldoba view point.}}\n; Coronation Bridge : An example of stunning architecture, also known as Sevoke bridge situates on lower Himalaya about 20&nbsp;km from Siliguri made up of steel in year 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=Coronation bridge facts|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> This bridge spans across [[Teesta River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1040805/asp/siliguri/story_3584709.asp|title=Coronation Bridge|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Darjeeling Himalayan Railway : [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|DHR]] or toy train that runs between [[New Jalpaiguri]], Siliguri and [[Darjeeling]] which was built between 1879 and 1881. This rail route is designated as [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944|title=Mountain Railways of India|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=darjnews>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingnews.net/darjeeling_himalayan_railway.html|title=History of DHR|accessdate=29 April 2019|work=darjeelingnews.net|publisher=Darjeelingnews}}</ref>\n\n;Bengal safari : Its about 8&nbsp;km away from Siliguri. [[North Bengal]] Wild Animals Park offers visitors an impressive opportunity to experience the wild and the untamed life closely (such as [[Jungle fowl]], [[Sambar deer]], [[Royal bengal tiger]], [[Wild boars]], [[Spotted deer]], [[Wild bear]], [[Rhinoceros]] etc.).It is fundamentally a part of the [[Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary]], spread over an area of 700 acre.Park conducts herbivore safari, carnivore safari, elephant safari etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shiliguri.com/bengal-safari-park|title=Bengal safari park|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northbengalwildanimalspark.in/|title=North Bengal wild animals park|website=www.northbengalwildanimalspark.in|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary : [[Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary]] is located 13&nbsp;km away from Siliguri on the foothills of the Himalayas,between [[Teesta River|Teesta]] and [[Mahananda River|Mahananda]].The sanctuary spans over 159 km2 of reserve forest. In 1959, it got the status of a sanctuary mainly to protect the [[Indian bison]] and [[Royal bengal tiger]]. This sanctuary is home to rare [[Mountain goat]], [[Chital]], [[Muntjac|Barking dear]], [[Fishing cat]], [[Sambar deer]], tiger, elephant and [[Indian bison]] and migratory birds. It offers mild to medium trekking challenges at some points.<ref>[http://www.westbengalforest.gov.in/ WBFD], West Bengal Forest Department.</ref>\n\n;North Bengal science centre : One and only science Centre of North Bengal established in 1997. The main attractions are Digital Planetarium, Science Shows (Super Cold Show-Showing low temperature properties of matter, Amazing Chemistry, Unexpected Science etc.), 3D Theater, Taramandal Shows, different science topic galleries and its green Science Park with T-Rex dinosaur statue at entrance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=North Bengal science centre attractions|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbscsiliguri.org/about-us.html|title=North Bengal science centre|website=nbscsiliguri.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Salugara monastery : located 6&nbsp;km away from Siliguri. Main attraction is the 100&nbsp;ft [[stupa]], which is believed to be founded by the Tibetan Lama, Kalu Rinpoche.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Salugara monastery|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> The ideal tranquil location for meditation was established by Tibetan monks and followers of [[Dalai Lama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/mobi/news/spectrum/bagpack-and-soak-in/612888.html|title=Salugara monastery|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;ISKCON temple : Also known as Sri Sri Radha Madhav Sundar Mandir, one of the biggest Krishna centres in the North-Eastern region of India. This temple was built by [[ISKCON]], which stands for International Society for Krishna Consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://centers.iskcondesiretree.com/siliguri/|title=ISCON Siliguri|website=centres.iscondesiretree.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Ewam India Buddhist monastery : located about 11&nbsp;km from Siliguri. Placed in the lap of nature nearby Bengal safari.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ewam.org/centers|title=Ewam India Buddhist monastery|website=www.ewam.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Sed-Gyued monastery : located nearby Salugara monastery. It is a breathtaking monument which was destroyed by the Army of China, and then rebuilt. The monastery is home to more than 90 monks of the Gelukpa division, and is used as a research centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sed-gyued.org/|title=Sed gyued monastery|website=www.sed-gyued.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Sevoke kali temple : An ancient temple on [[Teesta River|Teesta]] banks,in the lap of Himalaya, close to the [[Coronation Bridge]].This temple dedicated to [[Kali|Maa Kali]], the Goddess of Destruction and believed to be extremely powerful and divine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Sevoke kali mandir|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Hong Kong market : Hong Kong Market, apparently the Chandni Chowk of [[Northeast India]], is a street market with variety of shops popping out on the alleyways.It is the only place where anyone can get all imported (mainly China and southeast Asia) and branded products in low price.To get a great deal make sure you bargain big.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=About Hong Kong market|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Dreamland amusement park : located near [[Fulbari]], 12&nbsp;km from Siliguri junction, is an agricultural land converted in a fun house. It has 5-6 usual rides with a mini [[Ropeway]] also.\n\n;Savin kingdom : It is an amusement & water Park which is located near Dagapur in Siliguri. The park is a great place for fun and leisure in the nearby. The water park has pool, slides, artificial wave, rain dance etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Savin kingdom water park attractions|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> It also has various joy rides like adrenaline junkeis, sky train, break dance, go-carting, artificial bulls, etc. Multiplex, kids zone, restaurant are also out there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://savinkingdom.com/retreat|title=Savin kingdom Siliguri|website=savinkingdom.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Gajoldoba view point : Located about 28&nbsp;km from Siliguri, famous for the huge reservoir formed by Teesta barrage. This reservoir is home for variety of migratory birds (like [[River lapwing]], [[Great Crested Grebe]], [[Indian Cormorant]], [[Purple Heron]] , [[Eurasian Wigeon]], [[Common Shelduck]] , [[Cotton Teal]], [[Tufted Duck]], [[Little Ringed Plover]], [[Great Cormorant]] etc.). Due to shuttling of migratory birds, Pakhibitan sanctuary established here. One can spend time amidst the nature. Boating facility also available here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.north-bengal.com/gajaldoba-dooars.html|title=Gajoldoba view point-Mega tourism hub|website=www.north-bengal.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian international [[cricket]]er who plays [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for [[India national cricket team|Indian national team]].\n*[[Soumyajit Ghosh]] - The youngest [[India]]n player to qualify for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London, 2012 Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120513/spectrum/main6.htm|title=Ankita Das and Soumyajit Ghosh are the youngest Indian players to qualify for the 2012 London Olympics|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> He also became the youngest national champion at the age of 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/others/Soumyajit-Ghosh-becomes-youngest-national-table-tennis-champ/articleshow/17996714.cms|title=Soumyajit Ghosh becomes youngest national table tennis champ|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Ankita Das]] - Represented India at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[Table tennis at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's singles|Women's singles]] event.<ref name=champs>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/other-sports/sanil-ankita-are-national-champs/article5571879.ece|title=Sanil, Ankita are National champs|newspaper=The Hindu|date=13 January 2014|accessdate=1 May 2019|last1=Keerthivasan|first1=K.}}</ref>\n*[[Nandita Saha]] - She was a part of Indian trio, defeated Canada in Common wealth 2006 at Melbourne and won Bronze medal for India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thecgf.com/results/team/6241 | title=Table Tennis Team - Women Melbourne 2006 | publisher=thecgf.com | accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Sailendra Nath Roy]] - Guinness Book of World Record holder for the farthest distance travelled on a zip wire and pulled 40 tonnes [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|DHR]] toy train using hair.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/9553076/Man-pulls-train-with-hair-in-world-record-attempt.html|title=Man pulls train with hair in world record attempt|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 September 2012|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/man-uses-his-hair-to-pull-darjeeling-himalayan-train--17741.html|title=Man uses his hair to pull Darjeeling Himalayan train|publisher=indiatvnews.com|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Charu Majumdar]] \u2013 [[communist]] revolutionary from [[India]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Siliguri Jalpaiguri Development Authority]]\n* [[Siliguri subdivision]]\n* [[List of cities in West Bengal]]\n* [[List of metropolitan area in West Bengal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks |voy=Siliguri}}\n* [http://www.siligurismc.com/ Siliguri Municipal Corporation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070905172720/http://www.sjda.org/ Siliguri Jalpaiguri Development Authority]\n\n{{Darjeeling District}}\n{{Jalpaiguri district}}\n{{Municipalities of West Bengal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Jalpaiguri district]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Darjeeling district]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in West Bengal, India}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Siliguri\n| other_name                      =\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolitan City]] / [[Urban Agglomeration]]\n| image_s