Shamsia High Madrasah (Co-ed)\n\n;Army Schools\n*Army Public School (Bengdubi & Khaprail)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsbengdubi.org/|title=Army Public School, Bengdubi|website=Apsbengdubi.org|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Army Public School, Sukna<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apssukna.com/|title=Army Public School, Sukna|website=Apssukna.com|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*BSF Senior Secoundry School Kadamtala<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bsfschoolkadamtala.org/|title=BSF SENIOR SECONDARY RESIDENTIAL SCHOOL, Kadamtala, Darjeeling :: Welcome|website=Bsfschoolkadamtala.org|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*Kendriya Vidyalayas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kvsevokeroad.in/|title=Kendriya Vidyalaya, Sevoke Road :: Home Page|website=Kvsevokeroad.in|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Railway Schools\n*Bani Mandir Railway H.S. School (Co-ed)\n*New Jalpaiguri Railway Colony H.S. (Co-ed)\n*Railway Girls High School\n\n==Media==\n\n; Newspaper :English newspapers including [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.telegraphindia.com/north%20bangal/2019-06-06/72/Page-1.html|title=The Telegraph Siliguri edition epaper|website=epaper.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Times of India]] , [[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.thestatesman.com/t/9248|title=The Statesman Siliguri edition|website=www.uttarbangasambad.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> The Economic Time, [[The Asian Age]] are widely circulated throughout the city. Several Bengali newspaper including [[Uttarbanga Sambad]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uttarbangasambad.in/|title=Uttarbanga Sambad Siliguri edition|website=www.uttarbangasambad.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Anandabazar Patrika]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.anandabazar.com/topic/siliguri|title=Anandabazar Patrika Siliguri edition|website=www.anandabazar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Bartaman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bartamanpatrika.com/contact.php?cID=39|title=Bartaman Patrika Siliguri edition|website=www.bartamanpatrika.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Uttarer Saradin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highmediaindia.com/Media/contact_us.html|title=Uttarer Saradin-High Media Infotainment India Ltd.|website=www.highmediaindia.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> [[Aajkaal]], Pratidin, [[Ganashakti]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangla.ganashakti.co.in/#page1|title=Ganashakti patrika Siliguri edition|website=bangla.ganashakti.co.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> are available. Leading Hindi daily [[Prabhat Khabar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://epaper.prabhatkhabar.com/t/6235/Siliguri-City/?s=si|title=Prabhat Khabar Siliguri edition|website=epaper.prabhatkhabar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prabhatkhabar.com/news/west-bengal/siliguri/|title=Prabhat Khabar newspaper-Siliguri news|website=epaper.prabhatkhabar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> and Janpath Samachar<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janpathsamachar.com/epaper.php?pageid=page1&date=070619|title=Janpath Samachar Siliguri edition epaper|website=www.janpathsamachar.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> are also published from Siliguri. 'Himalaya Darpan' is a notable Nepali language newspaper which is circulated in Siliguri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaperhimalayadarpan.com/|title=Himalaya Darpan-news portal|website=www.epaperhimalayadarpan.com|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> An online based news portal, Siliguri Times<ref>{{cite web|url=https://siliguritimes.com/category/news/siliguri/amp/|title=SiliguriTimes-news portal|website=www.siliguritimes.com|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> is there for providing live updates regarding Siliguri and adjacent areas.\n\n;Radio : [[All India Radio]] Siliguri was commissioned in 1963 as an additional station of [[All India Radio|AIR Kolkata]].<ref name=\"AIR Siliguri-history\">{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=AIR Siliguri-history|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> It has two groups of transmitter i.e. high power BEL HMB 140 (AM) -2 [2\u00d7100 kW] and medium range GCEL 136 (FM) - 2 [2\u00d75 kW] for broadcasting programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/technical.html|title=AIR Siliguri-technical information|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> 'Prantik' was the first program broadcast from here in 1969.<ref name=\"AIR Siliguri-history\"/> In the course of time many notable individuals like [[Hemanta Mukhopadhyay]], [[Ustad Rashid Khan]], [[Subhash Mukhopadhyay (poet)|Subhas Mukhopadhyay]], [[Shashi Kapoor]], [[Manabendra Mukhopadhyay]], [[Madhuri Chattopadhyay]], Priya Ranjan Dasmunshi etc. visited [[All India Radio|AIR]] Siliguri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=Notable individuals visited AIR Siliguri|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Popular programs executing from here are Pratyusha, Yuva Anusthan, Grame Ganje, Mahila Majlis, Mananiyeshu, Sishumahal\u00a0and\u00a0Arogya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airsiliguri.in/history.html|title=Programs list of AIR Siliguri|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Two radio channels are operated from [[All India Radio|AIR]] Siliguri through which programs are broadcasting daily :\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| No.\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Name<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airsiliguri.in/station-profile.html|title=AIR Siliguri- broadcasting channels|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Frequency<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airsiliguri.in/station-profile.html|title=AIR Siliguri- frequency details|website=www.airsiliguri.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Language\n|-\n|01|| Primary Channel (PC) || PC: 421.9\u00a0Metres 711&nbsp;kHz (Medium wave) || Bengali\n|-\n|02|| Vividh\u00a0Bharati\u00a0Service (VBS) || VBS: 101.4&nbsp;MHz (High wave) || Bengali/Hindi\n|}\n\n:In addition to [[All India Radio]], Siliguri has several private FM radio channels :\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:95%; width:30%;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| No.\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Name<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiawaves.net/india/west-bengal-radio.htm#siliguri-radio|title=Siliguri FM channels names|website=www.asiawaves.net|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radio-asia.org/fm/fm.php?itu=India&region=WB|title=FM stations in West Bengal|website=www.radio-asia.org|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Frequency<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiawaves.net/india/west-bengal-radio.htm#siliguri-radio|title=Siliguri FM channels frequency|website=www.asiawaves.net|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n!  style=\"background:Pink; color:Black; text-align:center;\"| Language\n|-\n|01|| Nine FM || 91.9 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|02|| Radio High<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiohigh927fm.com/|title=Radio High 92.7 FM channel Siliguri|website=www.radiohigh927fm.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> || 92.7 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|03|| [[Red FM 93.5|Red FM]] || 93.5 FM || Hindi\n|-\n|04|| Radio Misty || 94.3 FM || Bengali \n|-\n|05|| Radio Mirchi || 98.3 FM || Bengali\n|-\n|06|| Air Rainbow<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlineradiofm.in/west-bengal/kurseong/fm-rainbow|title=Air rainbow Kurseong-Siliguri FM channel names|website=www.onlineradiofm.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> || 102.3 FM || Hindi/English\n|}\n\n;Television : Siliguri receives almost all television channels those are received by rest of the country. Apart from the national terrestrial network [[DD Bangla|Doordarshan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddbangla.gov.in/|title=DD Bangla-State owned channel|website=www.ddbangla.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://doordarshan.gov.in/|title=Doordarshan national|website=www.doordarshan.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> cable TV serves most of the houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://main.trai.gov.in/siliguri-internet-cable-tv-private-limited|title=Siliguri Internet & Cable TV Private Limited |website=main.trai.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccom.in/|title=CCN Siliguri cable network|website=www.cccom.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Siliguri also receives some Nepali<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abntv.in/|title=ABN TV Nepali TV channel|website=www.abntv.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> and Bangladeshi channels too. Siliguri has three local channels: CCN,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cccom.in/|title=CCN Siliguri|website=www.cccom.com|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> Amar Cable and HTV. There is a TV tower in Kurseong,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://doordarshan.gov.in/west-bengal-1|title=Doordarshan west Bengal stations|website=www.doordarshan.gov.in|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> about 25&nbsp;km from Siliguri.\n\n==Sports facilities==\nSiliguri hosts numerous sporting events and matches to influence and build up young athletes from the city.  Some of the important sports enthusiast local clubs in Siliguri organise several cricket, football, volleyball, swimming competition, TT matches etc.  S.A.I or [[Sports Authority of India]] in Kanchenjunga Stadium conducts football and athletics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkfile/File1374.pdf|title=Sports Authority of India-Siliguri|website=www.sportsauthorityofindia.nic.in|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> With the provision for an international outdoor and indoor stadium, Siliguri has enough opportunities to host national level matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/siliguri-prepares-for-big-battle/cid/1324566|title=Third I-League matches in Kanchanjunga stadium|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> This has also led to Siliguri being a prominent city to produce national champions like Mantu Ghosh, the Gold Medalist winner in the bi-annual South Asian Games (SAF) for table tennis, [[Ankita Das]],<ref name=\"champs\"/> [[Nandita Saha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/team/6241|title=Table Tennis Team-Women Melbourne 2006|publisher=thecgf.com|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> and [[Soumyajit Ghosh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120513/spectrum/main6.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref> another internationally acclaimed table tennis player and [[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian international [[cricket]]er who plays [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for [[India national cricket team|Indian national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;keeper=1;orderby=player;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;team=6;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|title=Wriddhiman Saha stats|website=espncricinfo|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> Siliguri has done a tremendous job for Indian table tennis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/siliguri-hailed-as-bhiwani-of-indian-tt-after-twin-oly-berth_741306.html|title=Siliguri hailed as Bhiwani of Indian TT|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=22 April 2012}}</ref> Also there is '''Bikash Ghosh Memorial Swimming Pool''' beside Kanchanjunga stadium in city which conducts swimming competitions there. White water rafting also done nearby the city in [[Teesta river]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.darjeeling-tourism.com/darj_0000f1.htm|title=white water rafting in Teesta river|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=400|caption_align=center\n| image1 = Sports 6.jpg|caption1=U-19 football tournament at [[Kanchenjunga Stadium]], Siliguri.\n| image2 = Sports 2.jpg|caption2=Municipal corporation indoor stadium.}}\n\n===Kanchenjunga stadium===\nThis is the main stadium in Siliguri,<ref>{{cite web | title =  Kanchenjunga Stadium in Siliguri |publisher=World Stadiums| url = http://www.worldstadiums.com/stadium_pictures/asia/india/siliguri_kanchenjunga.shtml | accessdate = 1 May 2019 }}</ref> a multipurpose stadium, mainly used for football matches although it hosted several cricket matches till date. It has a capacity of 30,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.millenniumpost.in/kolkata/kanchenjunga-stadium-set-to-get-a-facelift-342689|title=Kunchenjunga stadium-about|website=www.mellenniumpost.in|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=27 February 2019}}</ref> people at a time. Recently this stadium is all set to get a facelift.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kolkata24x7.com/kanchenjunga-stadium-set-to-get-major-makeover.html/|title=Kunchenjunga stadium all set to get facelift|website=www.kolkata24\u00d77.com|accessdate=1 May 2019|date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Football:''' \n*This stadium hosted [[Federation Cup (India)|Federation Cup 2012]] matches of India . The first ever [[Federation Cup (India)|Federation Cup]] played on this ground was between [[Mohun Bagan AC]] and [[Churchill Brothers S.C.]] in 2012.\n*Final match of the [[2013\u201314 Santosh Trophy]] was played at the stadium in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | title = Clinical Mizoram clinch 68th Santosh Trophy in style | url = http://www.saharasamay.com/sports-news/676549354/clinical-mizoram-clinch-68th-santosh-trophy-in-style.html|publisher=Samay Live |date=10 March 2014| accessdate = 1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*Seven rounds of [[2015 I-League 2nd Division]] match was played on this ground.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second division league venues finalized|url=https://www.the-aiff.com/news-center-details.htm?id=6248|website=The All India Football Federation|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*It also hosted two [[Kolkata Derby|kolkata derby]] matches in [[2015\u201316 I-League 2nd Division|2016 I-league]].\n*All the matches of [[2016 SAFF Women's Championship]] were played in the Kanchenjunga Stadium in Siliguri, [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SAFF Women\u00b4s Championship To Be Held in Siliguri|url=http://goalie365.com/show_details.php?article_id=774|website= goalie365.com | date=11 November 2016 | accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Kolkata Derby|Third I-League derby]] matches was held in this stadium ground in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/siliguri-prepares-for-big-battle/cid/1324566|title=Third I-League matches supposed to held in Siliguri|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Cricket:'''\n*This stadium has hosted 11 [[Ranji Trophy]] matches.The first ever [[Ranji Trophy]] played on this ground was between [[Bengal cricket team|Bengal]] and [[Punjab cricket team (India)|Punjab]] in 2010.\n*Two [[Celebrity Cricket League]] matches were played here. The first ever [[Celebrity Cricket League]] played on this ground was between [[Veer Marathi]] vs [[Karnataka Bulldozers]] and [[Telugu Warriors]] vs [[Bengal Tigers (Celebrity Cricket League)|Bengal Tigers]] in 2013.\n\n===Municipal corporation indoor stadium===\nIndoor sports including [[Table tennis]], [[Badminton]], [[Taekwon-do]], [[Lawn tennis]] and [[Chess]] are being played here.In fact Siliguri is renowned for being the training grounds of table tennis players.This stadium can hold 5000 people at a time. Senior National Table Tennis Championship<ref>{{cite web|title =National table tennis championships 2017 results|url=http://ttfi.org/cmspages/results/Result%20-%202017|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> was recently organised here.<ref>{{cite web|title =National table tennis championships|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/tournament-in-paddlers-hub-siliguri/cid/1524036|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref> Sports festival, 2017 also held in this indoor stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://siliguritimes.com/sports-festival-begins-indoor-stadium-siliguri/|title=Sports festival, Siliguri|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Visitors Attractions==\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=400|caption_align=center\n| image1 = Tourism 3.jpg|caption1=The [[Coronation Bridge]].\n| image2 = Tourism 2.jpg|caption2=Heritage [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|Toy Train]] at [[New Jalpaiguri Junction railway station|NJP]].\n| image3 = Tourism 5.jpg|caption3=Bengal safari park.\n| image4 = Tourism 8.jpg|caption4=Gajoldoba view point.}}\n; Coronation Bridge : An example of stunning architecture, also known as Sevoke bridge situates on lower Himalaya about 20&nbsp;km from Siliguri made up of steel in year 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=Coronation bridge facts|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> This bridge spans across [[Teesta River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1040805/asp/siliguri/story_3584709.asp|title=Coronation Bridge|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Darjeeling Himalayan Railway : [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|DHR]] or toy train that runs between [[New Jalpaiguri]], Siliguri and [[Darjeeling]] which was built between 1879 and 1881. This rail route is designated as [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/944|title=Mountain Railways of India|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=darjnews>{{cite web|url=http://www.darjeelingnews.net/darjeeling_himalayan_railway.html|title=History of DHR|accessdate=29 April 2019|work=darjeelingnews.net|publisher=Darjeelingnews}}</ref>\n\n;Bengal safari : Its about 8&nbsp;km away from Siliguri. [[North Bengal]] Wild Animals Park offers visitors an impressive opportunity to experience the wild and the untamed life closely (such as [[Jungle fowl]], [[Sambar deer]], [[Royal bengal tiger]], [[Wild boars]], [[Spotted deer]], [[Wild bear]], [[Rhinoceros]] etc.).It is fundamentally a part of the [[Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary]], spread over an area of 700 acre.Park conducts herbivore safari, carnivore safari, elephant safari etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shiliguri.com/bengal-safari-park|title=Bengal safari park|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northbengalwildanimalspark.in/|title=North Bengal wild animals park|website=www.northbengalwildanimalspark.in|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary : [[Mahananda Wildlife Sanctuary]] is located 13&nbsp;km away from Siliguri on the foothills of the Himalayas,between [[Teesta River|Teesta]] and [[Mahananda River|Mahananda]].The sanctuary spans over 159 km2 of reserve forest. In 1959, it got the status of a sanctuary mainly to protect the [[Indian bison]] and [[Royal bengal tiger]]. This sanctuary is home to rare [[Mountain goat]], [[Chital]], [[Muntjac|Barking dear]], [[Fishing cat]], [[Sambar deer]], tiger, elephant and [[Indian bison]] and migratory birds. It offers mild to medium trekking challenges at some points.<ref>[http://www.westbengalforest.gov.in/ WBFD], West Bengal Forest Department.</ref>\n\n;North Bengal science centre : One and only science Centre of North Bengal established in 1997. The main attractions are Digital Planetarium, Science Shows (Super Cold Show-Showing low temperature properties of matter, Amazing Chemistry, Unexpected Science etc.), 3D Theater, Taramandal Shows, different science topic galleries and its green Science Park with T-Rex dinosaur statue at entrance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=North Bengal science centre attractions|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbscsiliguri.org/about-us.html|title=North Bengal science centre|website=nbscsiliguri.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Salugara monastery : located 6&nbsp;km away from Siliguri. Main attraction is the 100&nbsp;ft [[stupa]], which is believed to be founded by the Tibetan Lama, Kalu Rinpoche.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Salugara monastery|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> The ideal tranquil location for meditation was established by Tibetan monks and followers of [[Dalai Lama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/mobi/news/spectrum/bagpack-and-soak-in/612888.html|title=Salugara monastery|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;ISKCON temple : Also known as Sri Sri Radha Madhav Sundar Mandir, one of the biggest Krishna centres in the North-Eastern region of India. This temple was built by [[ISKCON]], which stands for International Society for Krishna Consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://centers.iskcondesiretree.com/siliguri/|title=ISCON Siliguri|website=centres.iscondesiretree.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Ewam India Buddhist monastery : located about 11&nbsp;km from Siliguri. Placed in the lap of nature nearby Bengal safari.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ewam.org/centers|title=Ewam India Buddhist monastery|website=www.ewam.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Sed-Gyued monastery : located nearby Salugara monastery. It is a breathtaking monument which was destroyed by the Army of China, and then rebuilt. The monastery is home to more than 90 monks of the Gelukpa division, and is used as a research centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sed-gyued.org/|title=Sed gyued monastery|website=www.sed-gyued.org|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Sevoke kali temple : An ancient temple on [[Teesta River|Teesta]] banks,in the lap of Himalaya, close to the [[Coronation Bridge]].This temple dedicated to [[Kali|Maa Kali]], the Goddess of Destruction and believed to be extremely powerful and divine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Sevoke kali mandir|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Hong Kong market : Hong Kong Market, apparently the Chandni Chowk of [[Northeast India]], is a street market with variety of shops popping out on the alleyways.It is the only place where anyone can get all imported (mainly China and southeast Asia) and branded products in low price.To get a great deal make sure you bargain big.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/place/siliguri|title=About Hong Kong market|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Dreamland amusement park : located near [[Fulbari]], 12&nbsp;km from Siliguri junction, is an agricultural land converted in a fun house. It has 5-6 usual rides with a mini [[Ropeway]] also.\n\n;Savin kingdom : It is an amusement & water Park which is located near Dagapur in Siliguri. The park is a great place for fun and leisure in the nearby. The water park has pool, slides, artificial wave, rain dance etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wbtourismgov.in/destination/details/siliguri|title=Savin kingdom water park attractions|website=www.wbtourismgov.in|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> It also has various joy rides like adrenaline junkeis, sky train, break dance, go-carting, artificial bulls, etc. Multiplex, kids zone, restaurant are also out there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://savinkingdom.com/retreat|title=Savin kingdom Siliguri|website=savinkingdom.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Gajoldoba view point : Located about 28&nbsp;km from Siliguri, famous for the huge reservoir formed by Teesta barrage. This reservoir is home for variety of migratory birds (like [[River lapwing]], [[Great Crested Grebe]], [[Indian Cormorant]], [[Purple Heron]] , [[Eurasian Wigeon]], [[Common Shelduck]] , [[Cotton Teal]], [[Tufted Duck]], [[Little Ringed Plover]], [[Great Cormorant]] etc.). Due to shuttling of migratory birds, Pakhibitan sanctuary established here. One can spend time amidst the nature. Boating facility also available here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.north-bengal.com/gajaldoba-dooars.html|title=Gajoldoba view point-Mega tourism hub|website=www.north-bengal.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Wriddhiman Saha]] \u2013 Indian international [[cricket]]er who plays [[Test cricket|Test matches]] for [[India national cricket team|Indian national team]].\n*[[Soumyajit Ghosh]] - The youngest [[India]]n player to qualify for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London, 2012 Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120513/spectrum/main6.htm|title=Ankita Das and Soumyajit Ghosh are the youngest Indian players to qualify for the 2012 London Olympics|website=www.tribuneindia.com|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> He also became the youngest national champion at the age of 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/others/Soumyajit-Ghosh-becomes-youngest-national-table-tennis-champ/articleshow/17996714.cms|title=Soumyajit Ghosh becomes youngest national table tennis champ|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Ankita Das]] - Represented India at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[Table tennis at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's singles|Women's singles]] event.<ref name=champs>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/other-sports/sanil-ankita-are-national-champs/article5571879.ece|title=Sanil, Ankita are National champs|newspaper=The Hindu|date=13 January 2014|accessdate=1 May 2019|last1=Keerthivasan|first1=K.}}</ref>\n*[[Nandita Saha]] - She was a part of Indian trio, defeated Canada in Common wealth 2006 at Melbourne and won Bronze medal for India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thecgf.com/results/team/6241 | title=Table Tennis Team - Women Melbourne 2006 | publisher=thecgf.com | accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Sailendra Nath Roy]] - Guinness Book of World Record holder for the farthest distance travelled on a zip wire and pulled 40 tonnes [[Darjeeling Himalayan Railway|DHR]] toy train using hair.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/9553076/Man-pulls-train-with-hair-in-world-record-attempt.html|title=Man pulls train with hair in world record attempt|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 September 2012|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/man-uses-his-hair-to-pull-darjeeling-himalayan-train--17741.html|title=Man uses his hair to pull Darjeeling Himalayan train|publisher=indiatvnews.com|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Charu Majumdar]] \u2013 [[communist]] revolutionary from [[India]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Siliguri Jalpaiguri Development Authority]]\n* [[Siliguri subdivision]]\n* [[List of cities in West Bengal]]\n* [[List of metropolitan area in West Bengal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks |voy=Siliguri}}\n* [http://www.siligurismc.com/ Siliguri Municipal Corporation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070905172720/http://www.sjda.org/ Siliguri Jalpaiguri Development Authority]\n\n{{Darjeeling District}}\n{{Jalpaiguri district}}\n{{Municipalities of West Bengal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Jalpaiguri district]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Darjeeling district]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: long distance \u2192 long-distance, 1981-1991 \u2192 1981\u20131991 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siliguri"}
{"title_page": "When You Get a Little Lonely", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{For|the Nicolette Larson song|...Say When}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| type        = studio\n| artist      = [[Maureen McCormick]]\n| cover       = MaureenMcCormack111.jpg\n| border      = yes\n| alt         = The album cover for ''When You Get a Little Lonely''\n| released    = April 4, 1995\n| recorded    = 1994\u20131995\n| studio      = {{Flat list|\n* Nightingale Studios (Nashville)\n* Tempo Recording (Hollywood)\n}}\n| genre       = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length      = 34:41\n| label       = Phantom Hill\n| producer    = Barry Coffing (also [[Executive producer|exec.]])\n| misc        = {{Singles\n | name        = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = When You Get a Little Lonely\n | single1date = 1995\n | single2     = Tell Mama\n | single2date = September 1995\n}}\n}}\n'''''When You Get a Little Lonely''''' is the debut studio album by American actress and singer [[Maureen McCormick]]. It was released on April 4, 1995, through the [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill. After playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'', she was offered a solo record deal in the mid-1970s but rejected the offer to attend school. McCormick had previously recorded four albums as part of ''The Brady Bunch'' and a duet album with her co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]]. In 1994, she signed with her brother's record label, Phantom Hill, and recorded ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]]. Barry Coffing was the [[executive producer]] and arranged and produced all the songs. McCormick wanted to fuse genres into the album's overall [[Country music|country]] sound.\n\nThe album received mainly negative reviews; some reviewers were critical of McCormick's choice to record country music. She promoted it through live performances and [[Compact disc|CD]] signings. Its title track and \"Tell Mama\" were released as singles. ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was re-released in 2008 as a [[Circuit City]] exclusive. Since the album's release, McCormick has continued to perform country music and has participated in the [[reality television]] show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']]. In a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by restrictions to the recording process and wished she had written at least one song for it. ''When You Get A Little Lonely'' is her only album as a solo artist.\n\n== Background and recording ==\n[[File:Marcia, Marcia, Marcia.png|thumb|left|McCormick in a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional photo|alt=A 1971 photograph of Maureen McCormick as part of a 1971 ''The Brady Bunch'' promotional campaign.]]\n\n[[Maureen McCormick]] first rose to prominence while playing [[Marcia Brady]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Brady Bunch]]''. She entered the entertainment industry by performing [[jingle]]s; at the age of 10, she sang for a [[Kellogg's]] advertisement.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/145566910/|url-access=subscription|title=It's A Sunshine Day|last=Voger|first=Mark|date=May 21, 1995|work=[[Asbury Park Press]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> As a part of ''The Brady Bunch'' cast, she released four albums, the first of which she recorded at age 15. McCormick also released a duet album with her television co-star [[Christopher Knight (actor)|Christopher Knight]] in 1973.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Source4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|title=Maureen McCormick's top 5 country music moments|last=Miller|first=Victoria|date=September 8, 2015|publisher=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925093947/http://www.axs.com/maureen-mccormick-s-top-5-country-music-moments-88966|archivedate=September 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Victoria Miller, writing for the digital marketing platform [[AXS (company)|AXS]], considered her music with ''The Brady Bunch'' [[bubblegum pop]]; she cited the 1973 song \"[[It's a Sunshine Day]]\" as an example.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\nMcCormick, however, identified with [[country music]], saying she listened to the genre while growing up on her father's horse ranch.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> A \"country-tinged tune\" entitled \"Little Bird\" was among the songs on her album with Knight.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> When discussing her attraction to country, she said: \"I love songs that tell stories. Words to me are the most important thing.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperStory\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/177000915/|url-access=subscription|title=Maureen McCormick joins country music bunch|last=|first=|date=January 26, 1994|work=[[Florida Today]]|access-date=May 22, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> After ''The Brady Bunch'' ended in 1974, a company offered McCormick a record deal to record a country album, describing it as her \"natural sound\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She rejected the offer to return to college and pursue a more \"normal life\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|title=Maureen McCormick|last=McKechnie|first=Gary|date=May 28, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029051349/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-05-28/news/9506010699_1_maureen-mccormick-marcia-brady-brady-bunch|archivedate=October 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2008 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' interview, McCormick said she regretted not taking the deal, saying \"I think it would've been interesting to see where it would've gone.\"<ref name=\"EW1\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2008/03/03/a-chat-with-mau/|title=A chat with Maureen McCormick|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=March 3, 2008|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080512025450/http://popwatch.ew.com:80/popwatch/2008/03/a-chat-with-mau.html|archivedate=May 12, 2008|url-status=live|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In 1994, McCormick signed a recording contract with her brother's [[Record label|label]] Phantom Hill.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /><ref name=\"Source7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|last=Cooper|first=Tracie|title=Factsheet|website=[[AllMovie]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmovie.com/artist/maureen-mccormick-p47115|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During a 1995 [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] interview, she said; \"Music has always been my first love, and I've been waiting a long time for this opportunity. The wait just makes you stronger.\"<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\">{{cite journal|last=Atwood|first=Brett|date=April 1, 1995|title=TV: A Help or Hindrance to Musicians?|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|url-status=live|volume=107|issue=13|pages=8|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://books.google.com/books?id=6gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=%22Maureen+McCormick%22+%22Billboard%22&source=bl&ots=8zu947wzJV&sig=uRUHqu8nwKaBJCvAX6g-7urhBm4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja4ZbIxdbbAhVFrFMKHd8aCSIQ6AEIdDAT#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20McCormick%22%20%22Billboard%22&f=false|archivedate=June 15, 2018|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick recorded the album in 1994 and 1995 in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and [[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]].<ref name=\"Book1\">[[When You Get a Little Lonely#Peppiatt2004|Peppiatt (2004)]]</ref><ref name=\"Source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|title=AllMusic Review by Pemberton Roach|last=Roach|first=Pemberton|website=[[AllMusic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview1\" /> While in Nashville, she went to [[Music Row]] to find inspiration; after returning to California, she selected her favorite songs to include on ''When You Get a Little Lonely''.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had considered hundreds of songs before deciding on the eleven in the final track listing.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The [[executive producer]] Barry Coffing arranged and produced all of the tracks.<ref name=\"Source0\">{{cite AV media notes|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|date=April 4, 1995|others=[[Maureen McCormick]]|type=Inlay cover|publisher=Phantom Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"Coffing1\">{{cite book|title=When you get a little lonely|publisher=[[WorldCat]]|df=mdy-all|oclc = 32606771}}</ref> A 1994 episode of ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' included portions of the Nashville recording sessions.<ref name=\"Interview1\">{{cite interview|last=McCormick|first=Maureen|subject-link=Maureen McCormick|interviewer=[[Mary Hart]]|title=The Hart Files|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E7PWHDdyOww|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|publisher=[[Paramount Domestic Television]]|location=United States|date=March 8, 1994}}</ref> McCormick described the album as \"[her] debut singing\"; when asked about her past music career, she said, \"Well, those weren't solo songs. They were the Brady kids.\u00a0And that's not me anymore.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\">{{cite news|url=|title='Brady Kid' Has Grown-up Advice: Maureen McCormick Touts Birth Control|last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|date=March 10, 1994|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=|via=}}</ref> While completing ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', McCormick was offered a [[cameo role]] on ''[[The Brady Bunch Movie]]'' (1995) but turned it down to focus on the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> She had also been approached the previous year about the same cameo but was unable to accept because she was playing [[Betty Rizzo]] in a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of the musical [[Grease (musical)|''Grease'']].<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/135988293/|url-access=subscription|title=Here's the story of a girl named Brady|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=July 21, 1995|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Composition and sound ==\nMcCormick described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"country crossover\" and said, \"We tried to get some different styles, one that's upbeat, then there's a bluesy, jazzy, sexy song, then a commercial feeling\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> She listed [[Linda Ronstadt]], [[James Taylor]], [[Mary Chapin Carpenter]], and the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]] as her influences.<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> Discussing the song selection process, McCormick said she tried to \"get some different sounds together and have an album with a lot of a variety\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Pemberton Roach referred to the album as a \"completely straight-ahead modern Nashville country record\",<ref name=\"Source1\" /> while ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Alanna Nash described it as [[country pop]], citing its release as part of a trend of Hollywood celebrities recording music in Nashville.<ref name=\"Source5\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely/|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|last=Nash|first=Alanna|date=April 21, 1995|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120085719/http://www.ew.com/article/1995/04/21/when-you-get-little-lonely|archivedate=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The instruments used on ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' include [[pedal steel guitar]], fiddle, and piano, which a [[People (magazine)|''People'']] magazine contributor called \"all the twanging tools of the [country music] trade\", and wrote that McCormick adopted a \"Nashville accent\".<ref name=\"Source6\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|title=Picks and Pans Review: When You Get a Little Lonely|date=May 8, 1995|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-when-you-get-a-little-lonely-vol-43-no-18/|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe album credits include \"[[Music City]]'s finest\" ([[David Hungate]], J.D. Maness, and [[Larry Knechtel]]) and \"the usual suspects\" ([[Troy Seals]], [[Nicolette Larson]], and [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]).<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Mike Hughes, writing for ''[[The Times Herald]]'', described McCormick's [[Cover (music)|cover]] of [[Nicolette Larson]]'s 1985 single \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" as \"an [[uptempo|up-tempo]], [[Dancehall|dance-hall]] tune in current country style\".<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/211737147/|url-access=subscription|title=Robert Reed's influence lives in ''Brady'' sequels|last=Hughes|first=Mike|date=May 24, 1995|work=[[The Times Herald]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> She also covered [[Rena Gaile]]'s 1996 single \"[[Cloud of Dust]]\",<ref name=\"Source0\" /> and recorded a version of [[the Crickets]]' 1957 single \"[[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\" at the suggestion of [[Bread (band)|Bread]] front man [[David Gates]]. McCormick said \"Oh Boy!\" was her daughter's favorite song from the album.<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nLisa Gutierrez, writing for ''[[Democrat and Chronicle]]'', described ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as a \"truly grown-up work\" in comparison to her performance as Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick sings about sex using lyrics such as, \"He does me wrong, he does me right. He does me crazy in the middle of the night.\"<ref name=\"Newspaper2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176530073/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Seline|first=Anita M.|date=June 1, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Other lyrics include \"don't bury me on the love prairie\".<ref name=\"Newsday\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|title=Tube stars who laid down tracks|last=Bubbeo|first=Daniel|date=December 17, 2010|work=[[Newsday]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615234957/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/tube-stars-who-laid-down-tracks-1.2548138|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She also addresses \"loss [and] the Wild West\" in the songs.<ref name=\"Time\" /> American singer-songwriter [[Wayland Patton]] appears as a guest artist on \"We Must Have Done Something Right\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Source6\" />\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was released through Phantom Hill on April 4, 1995, on [[audio CD|CD]] and [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] formats.<ref name=\"Coffing1\" /><ref name=\"Source3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|title=Releases|website=[[AllMusic]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/releases|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> McCormick uploaded portions of the songs to her official website.<ref name=\"HighBeam1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|url-access=subscription|title=The Vagina Monologues: Of course Marcia had one; An interview with Maureen McCormick|date=February 4, 2003|work=[[Santa Fe Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-507289541.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"FabCD1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/how-to-write-a-sitcom-2132814|title=How To Write a Sitcom|last=Shulman|first=Dave|date=December 15, 2000|work=[[LA Weekly]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20010129093300/http://laweekly.com/ink/01/04/sitegeist-shulman.shtml|archivedate=January 29, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> McCormick, who was 38 at the time of the release, wanted to distance herself from the \"perpetual-teenager image\" of Marcia Brady.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> The packaging does not reference ''The Brady Bunch'';<ref name=\"Source1\" /> it includes a picture of a two-year-old McCormick dressed as a [[cowgirl]].<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> The cover, however, bore a sticker saying \"Marcia Marcia Marcia\", which McCormick said was done by a public relations company and described its inclusion as \"a ''big'' mistake\".<ref name=\"Newspaper1\" />\n\nMcCormick told ''Billboard'' she felt \"optimistic\" that [[country radio]] would accept her music.<ref name=\"SourceBillboard1\" /> During a 1995 interview, she said people, particularly [[DJ]]s, enjoyed the album and her voice; ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''{{'s}} Gary McKechnie wrote that it \"seem[ed] to be popular with country music fans\".<ref name=\"Orlando1\" /> The song \"When You Get a Little Lonely\" was the [[lead single]] and promoted through a [[music video]].<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /> The video was shown on the 1995 [[television special]] ''Brady Bunch Home Movies''.<ref name=\"NewspaperTimesHerald\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperStorm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178196364/|url-access=subscription|title=''The Brady Bunch'' and ''Laverne & Shirley'' get nostalgia treatment|last=Storm|first=Jonathan|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> \"Tell Mama\" was released in September 1995 as the second single.<ref name=\"NewspaperFried\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/275713505/|url-access=subscription|title=National Catfish Month survey says consumers like it fried|last=|first=|date=August 16, 1995|work=[[Clarksdale Press Register]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' was made available as a [[Digital download (music)|digital download]] on [[Apple Music]], but it was later removed from the platform.<ref name=\"DigitalDownload1\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|title=When You Get a Little Lonely|website=[[Apple Music]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615233727/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely/260546168|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Record label Building re-released the album as an exclusive for [[Circuit City]] in 2008.<ref name=\"Source3\" /> It is McCormick's only album as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Biopgraphy1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|title=Maureen McCormick Biography|date=August 31, 2016|work=Biography.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323140142/https://www.biography.com/people/maureen-mccormick-21273345|archivedate=March 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1994 ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' report, McCormick planned to promote ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' with a tour.<ref name=\"NewspaperSunTimes2\" /> She held album signings in 1995 at a Hollywood [[Virgin Megastores|Virgin Megastore]], the [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] [[record store]] Peaches Music & Video, and a [[Henrietta, New York|Henrietta]] [[Media Play]].<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /><ref name=\"HighBeam2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|url-access=subscription|title=Hot Tips Y'All Should Hear That Brady Gal Sing|date=April 24, 1995|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211105/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25001230.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"Orlando2\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|title=Who: Maureen McCormick, also known as Marsha Brady from...|date=May 17, 1995|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016150206/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-04-17/news/9504170063_1_marsha-brady-brady-bunch-peaches-music|archivedate=October 16, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of the Henrietta event, Media Play held a \"''Brady Bunch'' look-alike contest\".<ref name=\"Newspaper3\" /> McCormick promoted the album by performing at [[Lake Compounce]], an amusement park in Bristol and Southington, Connecticut, on July 2, 1995.<ref name=\"NewspaperPerformances\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/176664069/|url-access=subscription|title=Marsha! Marsha! Marsha!|last=|first=|date=June 29, 1995|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> On October 21, 1995, she performed during an [[Indianapolis Ice]] game against the [[Detroit Vipers]]. She also signed autographs during the game's intermission as part of a \"Brady Bunch Night\".<ref name=\"Newspaper6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/313324188/|url-access=subscription|title='Bunch' of fun is expected when 'Marcia' joins the Ice|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1995|work=[[Indianapolis News]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The following year, she sang at the Palmdale Playhouse in [[Palmdale, California]].<ref name=\"HighBeam3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|url-access=subscription|title=Palmdale Playhouse Opens '96 with Varied Fare|last=Thacker|first=Karen|date=January 8, 1996|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615211423/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-25037832.html|archivedate=June 15, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In August 2001, McCormick appeared alongside her ''The Brady Bunch'' co-stars on the game show [[The Weakest Link (U.S. game show)|''The Weakest Link'']]. On his official website, [[Barry Williams (actor)|Barry Williams]], who played [[Greg Brady (Brady Bunch)|Greg Brady]], held a competition in which viewers could win prizes, one of which was a copy of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'', for guessing the winner of ''The Weakest Link'' correctly.<ref name=\"Newspaper7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/279195610/|url-access=subscription|title='Brady Bunch' cast reunites to compete on NBC's 'Weakest Link'|last=|first=|date=August 25, 2001|work=[[The Morning Call]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"Source1\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|1|4}}<ref name=\"Newspaper5\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = F<ref name=\"Source5\" />\n| rev4 = ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n| rev4score = D\u2212<ref name=\"Time\" />\n}}\n''When You Get a Little Lonely'' received mainly negative reviews from critics. Some commentators recommended it for fans of ''The Brady Bunch''.<ref name=\"Source1\" /><ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> Pemberton Roach described McCormick as a \"competent singer\" with enthusiasm but said her [[upper register]] was \"a little screechy at times\". Roach cited \"Cloud of Dust\" as a highlight but was less positive about the album as a whole and said it \"sounds like a well-produced L.A. songwriter demo\".<ref name=\"Source1\" /> Despite praising the song selection, ''[[Hartford Courant]]''{{'s}} Anita M. Seline criticized McCormick's voice, specifically on her \"tepid\" version of \"Oh Boy!\".<ref name=\"Newspaper2\" /> A ''People'' writer suggested McCormick record pop music or covers of 1970s [[Top 40]] songs because \"kitschy stuff, after all, has a remarkable shelf life\". The reviewer said she \"doesn't bring much conviction to the material\" but her voice has a \"sweet, rather pure timbre&nbsp;... It's a very Brady sort of voice.\"<ref name=\"Source6\" /> Kathleen Adams and Lina Lofaro, writing for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' criticized McCormick's voice and said she \"shows scant vocal or emotional range and her backup musicians follow suit\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite journal|date=May 8, 1995|title=It didn't stop with William Shatner|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|volume=145|issue=19|pages=40|last1=Adams|first1=Kathleen|last2=Lofaro|first2=Lina|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators were critical of McCormick's decision to record country music. Alanna Nash panned ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"the most manufactured of country pop\" and criticized McCormick for singing with \"the overwrought exuberance of a high school variety show contestant\".<ref name=\"Source5\" /> ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''{{'s}} Miriam Longino wrote that she \"can carry a tune\" and that the album has the \"slickest arrangements and studio musicians\", but she largely dismissed it as \"a contrived attempt to cash in on country's popularity\". Longino said McCormick's interpretation of country music was inauthentic, writing, \"A pair of [[Tony Lama Boots|Tony Lama boots]] cannot transform this California actress into [[Patsy Cline]]\".<ref name=\"Newspaper5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/403240472/|url-access=subscription|title=''When You Get A Little Lonely''|last=Longino|first=Miriam|date=April 29, 1995|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''[[St. Cloud Times]]'' reviewer criticized her for \"tr[ying] her hand at country and go[ing] nowhere\".<ref name=\"Newspaper4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/225993301/|url-access=subscription|title=Country music's surge slows down in 1995|last=|first=|date=December 28, 1995|work=[[St. Cloud Times]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> A ''Time'' contributor dismissed ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' as \"new country curbed and gutted\".<ref name=\"Time\" /> In a 2010 ''[[Newsday]]'' article, Daniel Bubbeo wrote, \"it's doubtful [McCormick] caused [[Reba McEntire]] to have any sleepless nights\".<ref name=\"Newsday\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Maureen McCormick Maui crop.PNG|thumb|McCormick at a 2009 book signing|alt=A 2009 photograph of Maureen McCormick.]]\n\nIn a 2008 interview, McCormick said she was disappointed by the recording process for ''When You Get a Little Lonely'': \"I kinda felt like it wasn't done the right way. There are certain rules in Nashville, and my album didn't really follow them.\" She wished the process had been \"more organic\" and that she could have written at least one of the songs.<ref name=\"EW1\" />\n\nAccording to a 2015 AXS article, McCormick has \"long been associated with country music\", including her portrayal of [[Barbara Mandrell]] in the 1997 [[television film]] ''Get to the Heart: The Barbara Mandrell Story''.<ref name=\"Source4\" /> She [[Lip sync|lip-synced]] to Mandrell's music,<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/133287603/|url-access=subscription|title=Stretching It: From Marcia Brady to Barbara Mandrell|last=Thompson|first=Kevin D.|date=September 26, 1997|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> saying; \"Really, in a piece like this, you're playing that person. I would never be able to sound like her.\"<ref name=\"NewspaperKoko\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/2774745/|url-access=subscription|title=Barbara, Barbara, Barbara|last=Waldon|first=David Brian|date=September 15, 1997|work=[[Kokomo Tribune]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Also in 1997, McCormick was an opening act for [[Clint Black]] and [[Faith Hill]], and performed with [[Hal Ketchum]] and the [[Confederate Railroad]].<ref name=\"NewspaperPalm\" /><ref name=\"NewspaperDailyNews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/477521652/|url-access=subscription|title=There's a Song in Their Arts|last=Schulman|first=Sandra|date=August 31, 1997|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=May 21, 2019|location=|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nMcCormick appeared in the music video for [[Brad Paisley]]'s 2007 song \"[[Online (song)|Online]]\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> The following year, she competed on the first season of the reality television show [[Gone Country (TV series)|''Gone Country'']];<ref name=\"Source4\" /> as the prize, [[John Rich]] would produce the winner's song, and it would be sent to radio.<ref name=\"EW1\" /> McCormick said it was a \"lifelong dream to have a song on the radio\".<ref name=\"Source4\" /> In March 2008, [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]] was announced as the winner of the season.<ref name=\"CMT1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtpress.com/press-release/julio-iglesias-jr-tapped-by-host-john-rich-as-cmts-hit-series-gone-country-winner/|title=Julio Iglesias, Jr Tapped by Host John Rich as CMT's Hit Series ''Gone Country'' Winner|date=March 10, 2008|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Access Hollywood]]''{{'s}} executive producer Rob Silverstein hired McCormick as a red-carpet reporter for the [[2008 CMT Music Awards]] after seeing her on ''Gone Country''.<ref name=\"Source4\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits are taken from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely''. Barry Coffing produced all of the songs.<ref name=\"Source0\" />\n\n{{Tracklist\n| total_length    = 34:41\n| title1 = When You Get a Little Lonely\n| writer1 = [[Nicolette Larson]], Wendy Waldman, [[Josh Leo]]\n| length1 = 4:03\n| title2 = I'd Have to Call It Love\n| writer2 = [[Robert Ellis Orrall]]\n| length2 = 3:17\n| title3 = Tell Mama\n| writer3 = Barry Coffing\n| length3 = 3:03\n| title4 = Some Somebody\n| writer4 = [[Troy Seals]], [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]], Rhonda Gunn\n| length4 = 3:28\n| title5 = We Must Have Done Something Right\n| note5 = featuring [[Wayland Patton]]\n| writer5 = Marc Beeson, [[Liz Hengber]]\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = [[Cloud of Dust]]\n| writer6 = [[Judy Rodman]], Tom Damphier\n| length6 = 3:15\n| title7 = Go West\n| writer7 = [[Gretchen Peters]]\n| length7 = 2:53\n| title8 = [[Oh, Boy! (The Crickets song)|Oh, Boy!]]\n| writer8 = [[Norman Petty]], Bill Tilghman, Sonny West\n| length8 = 3:03\n| title9 = Might as Well Be Me\n| writer9 = [[Pam Tillis]], [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]\n| length9 = 2:52\n| title10 = I Do But I Don't\n| writer10 = [[Foster & Lloyd|Bill Lloyd]], Mark Irwin\n| length10 = 2:37\n| title11 = I Can't Say\n| writer11 = George Teren, Bob Regan\n| length11 = 2:41\n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nThe following credits were adapted from the booklet of ''When You Get a Little Lonely'' and AllMusic:<ref name=\"Source0\" /><ref name=\"Source2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|title=Credits|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615065322/https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-you-get-a-little-lonely-mw0000172134/credits|archivedate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* Richard Abramson&nbsp;\u2013 stylist\n* Osama Afifi&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* [[Barry Beckett]]&nbsp;\u2013 organ (Hammond)\n* Marc Beeson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Chris Bellman&nbsp;\u2013 mixing\n* Mike Botts&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Carter Bradley&nbsp;\u2013 make-up\n* Valerie Carter&nbsp;\u2013 vocals (background)\n* Barry Coffing&nbsp;\u2013 arranger, composer, piano, producer, vocals (background)\n* Jim Cox&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n* Tom Damphier&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Dan Dugmore&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, pedal steel\n* David Eaton&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n* [[Kenny Edwards]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals (background)\n* Jim Gaines&nbsp;\u2013 photography\n* Nicola Goode&nbsp;\u2013 cover design\n* Rhonda Gunn&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Liz Hengber&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Steve Hill&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* Randy Howard&nbsp;\u2013 fiddle, mandolin\n* Chris Hufford&nbsp;\u2013 engineer, mixing\n* David Hungate&nbsp;\u2013 bass\n* Mark Irwin&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Larry Knechtel]]&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n* Craig Krampf&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Bob Krusen&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n* Nicolette Larson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* [[Albert Lee]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* Josh Leo&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Bill Lloyd&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Jay Dee Maness&nbsp;\u2013 pedal steel\n* Maureen McCormick&nbsp;\u2013 primary artist, vocals\n* Gary Nicholson&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* Robert Ellis Orrall&nbsp;\u2013 composer\n* David Pascal&nbsp;\u